om\xc3\x91indication of the Supreme; tat\xc3\x91that; sat\xc3\x91eternal; iti\xc3\x91that; nirde\xe2\x80\x9ca\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91indication; br\xe2\x88\x92hma\xe2\x80\x9a\xe2\x88\x92\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91of the Supreme; tri-vidha\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91three kinds; sm\xe2\x80\x9eta\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91consider; brahma\xe2\x80\x9aa\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91the br\xe2\x88\x92hma\xe2\x80\x9aas; tena\xc3\x91therefore; ved\xe2\x88\x92\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91the Vedic literature; ca\xc3\x91also; yaj\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91sacrifice; ca\xc3\x91also; vihit\xe2\x88\x92\xc5\xa1\xc3\x91sacrifice; pur\xe2\x88\x92\xc3\x91formerly.
TRANSLATION
From the beginning of creation, the three syllables\xc3\x91om tat sat\xc3\x91have been used to indicate the Supreme Absolute Truth [Brahman]. They were uttered by \nbr\xe2\x88\x92hma\xe2\x80\x9aas while chanting Vedic hymns and during sacrifices, for the satisfaction of the Supreme.
PURPORTIt has been explained that penance, sacrifice, charity and foods are divided into three categories: the modes of goodness, passion and ignorance. But whether first class, second class or third class, they are all conditioned, contaminated by the material modes of nature. When they are aimed at the Supreme\xc3\x91om tat sat, the Supreme Personality of Godhead, the eternal\xc3\x91they become means for spiritual elevation. In the scriptural injunctions such an objective is indicated. These three words, om tat sat, particularly indicate the Absolute Truth, the Supreme Personality of Godhead. In the Vedic hymns, the word om is always found.\nOne who acts without following the regulations of the scriptures will not attain the Absolute Truth. He will get some temporary result, but not the ultimate end of life. The conclusion is that the performance of charities, sacrifice and penance must be done in the mode of goodness. Performed in the modes of passion or ignorance, they are certainly inferior in quality. The three words om tat sat are uttered in conjunction with the holy name of the Supreme Lord, e.g., om tad vi\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9ao\xc5\xa1. Whenever a Vedic hymn or the holy name \nof the Supreme Lord is uttered, om is added. This is the indication of Vedic literature. These three words are taken from Vedic hymns. Om ity etad brahma\xe2\x80\x9ao nedi\xc5\x92\xc4\xb1a\xe2\x80\xb9 n\xe2\x88\x92ma indicates the first goal. Then tattvamasi indicates the \nsecond goal. And sad eva saumya indicates the third goal. Combined they become om tat sat. Formerly when Brahm\xe2\x88\x92, the first created living entity, '
performed sacrifices, he spoke these three names of the Supreme Personality of Godhead. The same principle holds by disciplic succession. So this hymn has great significance. Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 recommends, therefore, that any work done should be done for om tat sat, or for the Supreme Personality of Godhead. When one performs penance, charity, and sacrifice with these three words, he is acting in Kr\xc5\x92na consciousness. K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is a scientific execution of transcendental activities which enables one to return home, back to Godhead. There is no loss of energy in acting in such a transcendental way.
